Murai was a disciple of {{ill|Konishi Raizan|ja|小西来山}}, editing Raizan’s posthumous collection, ''{{ill|Haikai Ima-miya-gusa|ja|俳諧今宮草}},'' and contributing to various haiku anthologies. However, despite his early exposure to haiku through his father, Murai's natural aptitude for the art form was limited, and his achievements as a haiku poet were overshadowed by his greater contributions as a local historian.{{sfn|''Haikai Ima-miya-gusa Compiler''|pp=381, 392}}

