At around the age of 20, Murai became interested in local history, producing works such as his magnum opus, ''{{ill|Nara Bōme Setsukai|ja|奈良坊目拙解}},'' which represented a significant departure from the tradition of temple- and shrine-focused local histories.{{sfn|''Haikai Ima-miya-gusa Compiler''|p=58}} His works incorporated a scientific approach, citing sources meticulously and critically evaluating oral traditions.{{sfn|''Nara Bōme Setsukai''|pp=414}}

