Murai was a disciple of {{ill|Konishi Raizan|ja|小西来山|qq=draft}}, editing Raizan’s posthumous collection, ''{{ill|Haikai Ima-miya-gusa|ja|俳諧今宮草|qq=draft}},'' and contributing to various haiku anthologies. However, despite his early exposure to haiku through his father, Murai's natural aptitude for the art form was limited, and his achievements as a haiku poet were overshadowed by his greater contributions as a local historian.{{sfn|''Haikai Ima-miya-gusa Compiler''|pp=381, 392}}

=== Interest in Local History ===
At around the age of 20, Murai became interested in local history, producing works such as his magnum opus, ''{{ill|Nara Bōme Setsukai|ja|奈良坊目拙解|qq=draft}},'' which represented a significant departure from the tradition of temple- and shrine-focused local histories.{{sfn|''Haikai Ima-miya-gusa Compiler''|p=58}} His works incorporated a scientific approach, citing sources meticulously and critically evaluating oral traditions.{{sfn|''Nara Bōme Setsukai''|pp=414}}

Kodō's historical writings were considered revolutionary in Nara’s historiography. Previous works, such as ''{{ill|Nara-zoku|ja|奈良曝|qq=draft}}'' and ''{{ill|Yamato Meisho-ki|ja|大和名所記|qq=draft}},'' often lacked rigor, relying heavily on oral accounts or focusing predominantly on religious sites.{{sfn|''Nara Bōme Setsukai''|p=414}} Kodō, however, expanded his scope to include the origins of towns and other secular topics, making ''Nara Bōme Setsukai'' the first comprehensive topographical history of Nara.{{sfn|''Nara Bōme Setsukai''|pp=413, 414}}

== Legacy and Rediscovery ==
Kodō’s works were often attributed incorrectly to his contemporary, {{ill|Hiramatsu Baichi|ja|平松倍千|qq=draft}}, leading to centuries of confusion about his identity. This misattribution was only corrected in the mid-20th century when researchers such as Kanai Toranosuke identified Kodō as the true author of ''Nara Bōme Setsukai'' and other important historical texts.{{sfn|''Haikai Ima-miya-gusa Compiler''|p=389}}

