Kodō's historical writings were considered revolutionary in Nara’s historiography. Previous works, such as ''{{ill|Nara-zoku|ja|奈良曝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara-zoku|qq=}}'' and ''{{ill|Yamato Meisho-ki|ja|大和名所記|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Meisho-ki|qq=}},'' often lacked rigor, relying heavily on oral accounts or focusing predominantly on religious sites.{{sfn|''Nara Bōme Setsukai''|p=414}} Kodō, however, expanded his scope to include the origins of towns and other secular topics, making ''Nara Bōme Setsukai'' the first comprehensive topographical history of Nara.{{sfn|''Nara Bōme Setsukai''|pp=413, 414}}

== Legacy and Rediscovery ==
Kodō’s works were often attributed incorrectly to his contemporary, {{ill|Hiramatsu Baichi|ja|平松倍千|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiramatsu Baichi|qq=}}, leading to centuries of confusion about his identity. This misattribution was only corrected in the mid-20th century when researchers such as Kanai Toranosuke identified Kodō as the true author of ''Nara Bōme Setsukai'' and other important historical texts.{{sfn|''Haikai Ima-miya-gusa Compiler''|p=389}}

